<a name="broad"></a>
<font class="subhead">Broadband Equals Faster Speeds, Bigger Pipes</a></font><p>
<font class="body">
If you’ve ever whiled away the time as large Internet files download, or fretted about how to share MP3 files 
and watch video more easily, then broadband may be a welcome addition to your home. Broadband is high-speed 
transmission in which a single cable can carry several channels of data at once, providing integrated access 
to voice, data, video-demand services and interactive delivery. The most common type of broadband transmission 
is cable wiring (as in cable modems) and digital subscriber lines (DSL).
<p>
Broadband gives you the ability to connect to the Internet almost instantly—turn on your computer, and you’re 
online. Websites load quickly (even with lots of graphics) and video watching becomes easier. Topping the list 
for applications for broadband is home networking, the ability to wire PCs, TVs and other devices so that they 
share resources and a single Internet connection.
<p>
A broadband connection is still a luxury—only about 5 percent of homes in the United States have broadband. 
Most people use dial-up connections, but demand is increasing for the speedy connections, with websites that 
include streaming media and other new services driving broadband demand. Another trend is the increase in 
wireless Internet use. As more people use wireless to access the Internet, demand may increase for streamlined, 
customized versions of website content.
<p>
Recent CEA research found that some consumers are interested in a high-speed connection to the Internet 
(10 times the speed of their current connection), assuming the price was a flat rate of $50 per month.
<p>
7% - Very Interested<br>
26% - Somewhat Interested<br>
66% - Not At All Interested<br>
<p>
<u>Cable, DSL Compete for Customers</u>
<p> 
The two main players in the broadband market are cable operators (for cable modem) and telephone companies 
(for digital subscriber line, or DSL). The cable industry has been rolling out cable modems across the country, 
trying to leverage their existing video relationship with the consumer to create a bundle of video, voice and 
data services. Meanwhile, telephone companies, who have a jump on the data side, are pushing DSL, a high-speed 
data technology that enables high speeds over existing phone lines. 
<p>
Each technology has its advantages and disadvantages. With cable modem, speeds are hard to predict because fat 
fiber pipes lead to neighborhood "nodes" that split into a web of spider-like cable lines. The bandwidth from 
that point is shared among the homes served by that node, so speeds depend on how many people are receiving bits 
at any given time. 
<p>
DSL services, on the other hand, are dedicated to each household, so they can deliver a particular speed. However 
DSL has trouble sending data over long distances. The FCC estimates that DSL and cable modems will have comparable 
subscriber levels by 2007.
<p>
<u>Getting Rid of Bottlenecks</u>
<p>
As broadband comes to homes, new broadband applications could spur new services, including video phones, wireless 
touchscreens, virtual real estate shopping or most anything that consumers believe may improve their lives. 
<p>
To enable broadband networking of appliances, houses built more than 20 years ago may need to run entirely new wiring 
through existing conduits. Several companies are retrofitting existing houses to make the best use of broadband 
services. Audiophiles and gamers could prove to be the biggest markets for the makers of broadband devices. People 
could network MP3 audio files throughout their houses or play video games from different rooms with other family 
members.
<p>
Several companies have jumped in to outfit homes of the future with broadband appliances and connectivity. IBM, for 
example, has been pushing its Home Director product to encourage homebuilders and homeowners to include high-speed 
data connections. Eventually, broadband connectivity may come to be thought of as an essential factor, like air 
conditioning, when considering which new home to buy. 
<p>
