<font class="subhead">Digital Imaging</font><p>


When senior citizens with digital camcorders are merrily
sending and receiving videos of their grandchildren, you know digital imaging
is expanding in ways that were out of reach only a year or two ago. Digital
cameras and camcorders, software editing packages, and storage and printing
options offer opportunities aplenty. 
<p>
According to the Consumer Electronics Association’s (CEA)
"Digital Camera Owners Profile" survey, 80 percent of owners said
they had e-mailed a photo taken with a digital camera, 82 percent have printed
a photo and 26 percent viewed a photo on their TV. Nearly 48 percent of owners
say the main reason for purchasing a digital camera was to post pictures to a
website. Little difference was found among gender, age or income segments when
considering usage. 
<p>
Digital imaging will be among the most talked
about technologies at the 2002 International CES. Prices are coming down as
sales of digital cameras and camcorders continue to rise, and online photo
sites are attracting traditional camera users to the digital marketplace.
Consumers have become more aware of products that allow them to manipulate and
control content. Software is more powerful, hard drive capacities have
increased and the speed of processors and video graphics cards allows users to
do real-time editing on the computer. 
