<a name="homeNetworking"></a>
<br>
<font class="subhead">Home Networking</font><p>


More people are equipping their houses with networked
systems that can control everything from distributing television and Internet
content to programming their alarm systems. Imagine returning home after work
and simultaneously adjusting the temperature and tuning in your favorite high
definition TV (HDTV) broadcast, all while checking your e-mail. This networked
home can be installed easily and inexpensively today. 
<p>
But you don’t have to be at home to control appliances,
lights and other devices. Logging onto a password-protected site via a Web
browser, a user can remotely check on such things while away from home.
Virtually any digital source—a DVD, a CD player or a TV—can be controlled
through a handheld remote, an LCD touchscreen or even by voice.</p>
<p>
The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) defines a home
network as one that facilitates communication among the appliances, home
systems, entertainment products and information devices in a home, so they can
share information. This allows users to control home systems.
The home network includes lighting, audio/video system
components, temperature control, security, telephone/communications, the
personal computer network, Internet service, utilities and power and even
controlling drapes and blinds. 
<p>
Many products now allow
  appliances, home systems and electronic devices to communicate through
  dedicated wires, wirelessly via radio frequency or through a home's existing
  wiring. 
<p>
  CEA is working on the Tech Home Rating System that will
allow homebuyers, builders and sellers to rate the technological capabilities
of a home. 
<p>
Users will increasingly demand always-on
Internet service, via digital subscriber line (DSL) service or an integrated
services digital network (ISDN) line. One of the key drivers in the connected
lifestyle is the ability to have multiple family members surfing the Net
simultaneously from different locations in the home. This means that instead of
stand-alone computers in various rooms of the house, one computer in a central
location functions as a hub. Instead of low-cost printers by each computer, a
laser printer next to the hub PC can print the kids' school projects. And
entertainment content such as music and video are among the most popular types
of content consumers would like distributed around the house, earning 59 and 47
percent respectively, according to a CEA survey in 2000.
