<a name="teleworking"></a>
<br>
<font class="subhead">Teleworking</font><p>
As employees and organizations continue to experiment with alternative work
arrangements and as flexible scheduling grows common, the Internet and advanced
communication products are enabling home-based workers to have the same access
to online resources as their colleagues and competitors who work in traditional
settings. 
<p>
Teleworking
allows employees to schedule home and work activities as necessary and gives
them the flexibility to manage their time. The increased emphasis on speed and
accountability in the new economy is quickly replacing the idea that "face
time" at the office is the most important thing. Instead of being
responsible for their time, teleworkers now are responsible for their work
product.
<p>
This blurring of work and home life is being enabled by digital technology that
allows an office to be located anywhere—the city, the suburbs or a mountain
top—using a range of workstyle products including pagers, wireless phones,
PDAs, laptops and of course, the desktop PC. Digital imaging, wireless devices,
Internet access devices, portable peripherals and handheld navigational
equipment are the epitome of "convergence" incorporating technology
from the telecom, PC and consumer electronics industries. 
