<a name="dvd"></a>
<br>
<font class="subhead">DVD-Audio</font><p>

DVD, the fastest selling product in the history of consumer
electronics, is driving the surround experience.Considering its many applications for audio, video and data, it
truly is a “digital versatile disc.”
<p>
DVD-ROM drives are fast becoming a standard feature, making
surround sound a reality on our PCs either through a four- or five-channel
speaker system, or through a two-speaker array creating a virtual experience.
Since the user is in a near-field listening environment, either approach is
effective.
<p>
In 2000, CEA numbers show factory sales of DVD-Video players
to be more than 6.6 million units. For 2001, sales are projected to exceed 9
million units, ringing up more than $2 billion in total factory sales. In
addition to playing movie soundtracks in Dolby Digital or DTS, DVD-Video
players can play the new 5.1 multichannel music discs, which appeared on the
market in anticipation of a DVD-Audio solution.The success of DVD in the marketplace should guarantee the
success of any new DVD-based mulitchannel audio format such as DVD-Audio and
Super Audio CD (SACD).
<p>
Surround music means that at home, you will be
able to hear music the same way the musicians and engineers do while playing or
mixing music. The sonic realism and depth of this new listening experience is
dramatically different from what we have come to expect.
